newsitem.title: INDONESIA: Jakarta call money rises to 13.5 percent.
newsitem.headline: Jakarta call money rises to 13.5 percent.

text.p: Jakarta call money rose to 13.5 percent from 11.5 percent on Friday morning following some tightening in the money market, dealers said.
They attributed the rise to larger than expected weekly tax payments amid an early central bank injection of some 715 billion rupiah on the market.
Overnight swaps were also driven up by the tightening to 2.0 points from 1.35 points at the opening.
However, longer-term rates were stable, with one-month money quoted at 13.75/14.00 percent and three-month at 15.0/15.125. Longer-term swap rates were also stable.
The average overnight interbank rate on Thursday was 9.92 percent, compared with 10.46 percent on Wednesday.
